attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, ARM, version 1 (ARM), statically linked, stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This ARMv7 ELF binary is a multi-functional botnet agent, likely a variant of the Gafgyt (Bashlite) or Mirai families. It exhibits several definitive malicious behaviors: 1) Brute-forcing: Function sub_137c8 contains a massive dictionary of hardcoded default credentials (e.g., 'root:xirtam', 'admin:admin1234') for automated Telnet/SSH attacks. 2) DDoS Capabilities: Functions sub_a054, sub_9164, and sub_9918 contain logic for raw socket manipulation and manual TCP/IP packet construction, typical of SYN/UDP flooding engines. 3) Competing Process Termination: It enumerates /proc to identify and kill rival malware or security tools by checking process names and command lines (sub_1181c, sub_11194). 4) Payload Delivery: It utilizes command templates for downloading and executing secondary scripts via wget, curl, tftp, and ftpget. 5) Persistence: It employs /proc/self/exe to replicate itself and manipulate file permissions for execution.
